2026-07-14 00:17:17.833 [info] From claude: 2026-07-13T22:17:17.831Z [DEBUG] "Hook PreToolUse:Write (PreToolUse) success:\n{\"session_id\":\"1259c791-eb4e-46ae-b33e-663aba03788a\",\"transcript_path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\z00571dh\\\\.claude\\\\projects\\\\c--Users-z00571dh-Documents-assignment\\\\1259c791-eb4e-46ae-b33e-663aba03788a.jsonl\",\"cwd\":\"c:\\\\Users\\\\z00571dh\\\\Documents\\\\assignment\",\"prompt_id\":\"fa24a644-88ef-4e75-b762-b43938e4bbf6\",\"permission_mode\":\"acceptEdits\",\"agent_id\":\"a637caa46ec92417e\",\"effort\":{\"level\":\"medium\"},\"hook_event_name\":\"PreToolUse\",\"tool_name\":\"Write\",\"tool_input\":{\"file_path\":\"c:\\\\Users\\\\z00571dh\\\\Documents\\\\assignment\\\\docs\\\\TASKS.md\",\"content\":\"# Implementation Tasks: Legal Investigation Agent\\n\\nTasks are ordered to minimise project risk. Each milestone leaves the repository in a\\nrunnable state. The eval harness and document corpus are already built and are the\\nstarting point for all milestones.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Milestone 0 — Project Skeleton (Already Complete)\\n\\nThe following are already in place and require no further work:\\n\\n- `data/documents/` — 7 synthetic legal documents\\n- `eval/rubric.py` — 10 LLM judge criteria\\n- `eval/scenarios.py` — 4 test scenarios\\n- `eval/harness.py` — runnable scorer with stub mode\\n- `docs/PRD.md`, `docs/architecture.md`\\n\\n**Runnable state:** `python eval/harness.py --all` executes in stub mode, prints\\nper-criterion table, scores 0% (stub report). This confirms the harness is wired\\ncorrectly before the agent exists.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Milestone 1 — State and Tools\\n\\n**Goal:** Define the shared data contract and implement all local tools. No LLM calls.\\nThe eval harness stub mode must still pass after this milestone.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Task 1.1 — State Dataclasses\\n\\n**Goal:** Define `Note` and `InvestigationState` — the shared data contract imported\\nby both `runner.py` and `planner.py`.\\n\\n**Files affected:**\\n- `agent/state.py` (create)\\n- `agent/__init__.py` (create, empty)\\n\\n**Acceptance criteria:**\\n- `InvestigationState` can be instantiated with a goal and empty collections\\n- `Note` accepts `kind` values: `\\\"finding\\\"`, `\\\"gap\\\"`, `\\\"conflict\\\"`\\n- Both dataclasses have readable `__repr__` (default from `@dataclass`)\\n- File is under 30 lines\\n\\n**Tests:**\\n- Import `InvestigationState` and `Note` in a Python shell without error\\n- Create one of each kind of Note and append to `state.notes`\\n- Serialise `state.__dict__` to JSON without error (verifies eval harness can log it)\\n\\n**Risks:**\\n- None. This is pure data definition.\\n\\n**Engineering quality evidence:**\\n- Reviewer sees one dataclass with a `kind` field rather than three separate dataclasses.\\n  This demonstrates the judgment call documented in `architecture.md`.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Task 1.2 — Tool Implementations\\n\\n**Goal:** Implement the three local tools. Each must handle missing files and empty\\nresults without raising exceptions.\\n\\n**Files affected:**\\n- `agent/tools.py` (create)\\n\\n**Acceptance criteria:**\\n- `list_files(directory)` returns a sorted list of `.txt` filenames; returns `[]` if\\n  directory is empty or missing\\n- `read_file(directory, filename)` returns file contents truncated to 3,000 characters;\\n  returns `\\\"\\\"` if file does not exist\\n- `search_in_file(directory, filename, query)` returns matching lines (case-insensitive),\\n  up to 20 lines; returns `\\\"\\\"` if file missing or no match\\n- No tool raises an unhandled exception under any input\\n\\n**Tests:**\\n- Call each tool against the real `data/documents/` corpus and verify output format\\n- Call each tool with a filename that does not exist — verify `\\\"\\\"` or `[]` returned,\\n  not an exception\\n- Call `search_in_file` with a query that has no matches — verify `\\\"\\\"` returned\\n- Call `read_file` on a file longer than 3,000 characters — verify truncation\\n\\n**Risks:**\\n- Path handling on Windows (backslash vs forward slash). Use `pathlib.Path` throughout.\\n\\n**Engineering quality evidence:**\\n- Tools are pure functions with no side effects beyond reading files.\\n- Truncation constants are inlined as literals — not named constants, because each\\n  value appears exactly once.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Milestone 2 — Minimal Agent Loop (No Replanning)\\n\\n**Goal:** A working agent that plans, executes tools, observes results, and produces a\\nfinal report — but does not yet replan. Covers the happy path end-to-end.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Task 2.1 — Planner: Plan and Conclude\\n\\n**Goal:** Implement `planner.plan()` and `planner.conclude()`. These are the two LLM\\ncalls that bookend the loop. Implementing them first allows the loop to run end-to-end\\neven before observe and replan exist.\\n\\n**Files affected:**\\n- `agent/planner.py` (create)\\n\\n**Acceptance criteria:**\\n- `plan(goal, available_docs)` returns a non-empty `list[str]` of investigation questions\\n- The plan always includes at least one question touching each of the 5 investigation\\n  categories\\n- `conclude(state)` returns a non-empty string report that references the goal\\n- Both functions call the OpenAI API using the key from `OPEN_AI_KEY` env var\\n- Both use `temperature=0`\\n- Prompts are defined inline in each function — no separate prompt module\\n\\n**Tests:**\\n- Call `plan(\\\"Can Orion Capital safely acquire Nexus Legal Technologies?\\\", [list of docs])`\\n  and verify: returns a list, length >= 5, each item is a non-empty string\\n- Call `conclude` with a state containing two findings and one gap — verify the report\\n  string mentions the goal and at least one finding\\n- Verify API key error raises a readable message, not an unhandled `AuthenticationError`\\n\\n**Risks:**\\n- OpenAI API latency in tests. Accept that these tests make real API calls — no mocking.\\n- Plan quality: if the plan is too generic, the loop will produce shallow results.\\n  Prompt must name the 5 investigation categories explicitly.\\n\\n**Engineering quality evidence:**\\n- System prompt defines the agent's role and the 5 categories.\\n- User prompt provides only goal and filenames — not document contents. This demonstrates\\n  the context discipline described in `architecture.md`.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Task 2.2 — Planner: Select Tool and Observe\\n\\n**Goal:** Implement `planner.select_tool()` and `planner.observe()`. These are the two\\ncalls inside the loop body.\\n\\n**Files affected:**\\n- `agent/planner.py` (extend)\\n\\n**Acceptance criteria:**\\n- `select_tool(state, question)` returns `{\\\"tool\\\": str, \\\"args\\\": dict}` where `tool` is\\n  one of `list_files`, `read_file`, `search_in_file`\\n- `observe(state, question, raw_result)` returns\\n  `{\\\"note\\\": Note, \\\"decision\\\": \\\"continue\\\"|\\\"replan\\\"|\\\"conclude\\\"}`\\n- Both use `response_format={\\\"type\\\": \\\"json_object\\\"}`\\n- State passed to both is a concise summary (~200 tokens), not raw message history\\n- Raw tool result passed to `observe` is truncated before being included in the prompt\\n\\n**Tests:**\\n- Call `select_tool` with a question about IP ownership and verify it returns a valid\\n  tool name and plausible args\\n- Call `observe` with a non-empty result and verify `decision` is `\\\"continue\\\"` and\\n  `note.kind` is `\\\"finding\\\"`\\n- Call `observe` with an empty result (`\\\"\\\"`) and verify `decision` is `\\\"replan\\\"` or\\n  `\\\"conclude\\\"` and `note.kind` is `\\\"gap\\\"`\\n- Verify JSON parse failure on malformed API response is caught and returns a safe default\\n\\n**Risks:**\\n- LLM occasionally returns invalid JSON despite `json_object` format. Wrap parse in\\n  try/except with a safe fallback (gap note, continue decision).\\n- `select_tool` may hallucinate a tool name not in the allowed set. Validate against\\n  the known list and default to `read_file` if invalid.\\n\\n**Engineering quality evidence:**\\n- Two separate LLM calls for tool selection and observation, not one combined call.\\n  This is a concrete prompt engineering judgment documented in `architecture.md`.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Task 2.3 — Runner: Loop and Logging\\n\\n**Goal:** Implement `runner.py` — the loop, tool dispatch, `_log` helper, and the\\npublic `run_investigation` function. This is the file that ties everything together.\\n\\n**Files affected:**\\n- `agent/runner.py` (create)\\n\\n**Acceptance criteria:**\\n- `run_investigation(goal, documents_dir)` returns a non-empty string report\\n- Loop terminates when `status == \\\"concluding\\\"` or `iterations >= 10`\\n- Tool dispatch is a `match` statement on the tool name — no dynamic dispatch\\n- `_log(event, payload)` writes to stdout (prefixed, human-readable) and appends\\n  a JSON line to `logs/run_<timestamp>.jsonl`\\n- `logs/` directory is created automatically if it does not exist\\n- A full run against the real corpus completes without unhandled exceptions\\n- The agent can be invoked from CLI: `python -m agent.runner \\\"Can Orion Capital...\\\"`\\n\\n**Tests:**\\n- Run against Scenario S1 corpus (all 7 documents) — verify a report is returned\\n- Verify `logs/` contains a JSONL file after the run\\n- Verify the JSONL file contains at least one entry per event type:\\n  `plan`, `tool_call`, `observation`, `report`\\n- Run with a corpus directory containing no documents — verify graceful conclusion\\n  (report says evidence unavailable), not a crash\\n\\n**Risks:**\\n- Loop may not terminate if `observe` always returns `\\\"continue\\\"`. The `MAX_ITERATIONS`\\n  guard is the safety net — verify it triggers correctly.\\n- Logging file handle left open on exception. Use a write-and-close pattern per log\\n  entry, not a persistent file handle.\\n\\n**Engineering quality evidence:**\\n- `runner.py` is the thinnest possible orchestrator — it calls planner functions and\\n  tools, and nothing else. A reviewer can read the loop body and understand the full\\n  agent lifecycle without opening any other file.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Milestone 2 Gate\\n\\nRun `python eval/harness.py --scenario S1` against the real agent (not stub).\\nThe harness must return a non-zero score. The JSONL trace must exist.\\nThis is the first end-to-end validation.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Milestone 3 — Replanning\\n\\n**Goal:** Add `planner.replan()` and wire it into the runner. This is the component\\nthat directly demonstrates adaptive behaviour — the core of the 40% harness score.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Task 3.1 — Planner: Replan\\n\\n**Goal:** Implement `planner.replan()`. Called when `observe` returns `\\\"replan\\\"`.\\nMust return revised remaining steps without discarding already-answered findings.\\n\\n**Files affected:**\\n- `agent/planner.py` (extend)\\n\\n**Acceptance criteria:**\\n- `replan(state)` receives the full state (including existing notes and gaps)\\n- Returns a `list[str]` of revised remaining questions — not a full new plan\\n- Prompt explicitly instructs the planner: \\\"do not repeat questions already answered;\\n  focus on the gap or conflict that triggered replanning\\\"\\n- If replanning produces no new steps, returns an empty list (triggering conclude)\\n- Uses `temperature=0.3` (slight creativity needed for recovery)\\n\\n**Tests:**\\n- Call `replan` with a state that has one gap (litigation register missing) — verify\\n  the returned steps include a fallback search strategy\\n- Call `replan` with a state that has a conflict — verify the returned steps include\\n  an instruction to cross-reference the conflicting sources\\n- Call `replan` with a state where all questions are answered (no gaps) — verify\\n  it returns `[]`\\n\\n**Risks:**\\n- Replanner may regenerate already-answered questions. The prompt must include the\\n  list of already-answered questions explicitly.\\n- Infinite replan loop if every replan step also results in a gap. The `MAX_ITERATIONS`\\n  guard in the runner is the backstop.\\n\\n**Engineering quality evidence:**\\n- Replanning preserves existing findings — it does not start over. This demonstrates\\n  stateful adaptation, not blind retry.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Task 3.2 — Wire Replanning into Runner\\n\\n**Goal:** Handle the `\\\"replan\\\"` decision in the runner loop and log the replan event.\\n\\n**Files affected:**\\n- `agent/runner.py` (extend)\\n\\n**Acceptance criteria:**\\n- When `observe` returns `decision: \\\"replan\\\"`, runner calls `planner.replan(state)`\\n- Revised steps replace `state.plan[state.current_step:]` — preserving completed steps\\n- `_log(\\\"replan\\\", {...})` is called with the reason and new steps\\n- `state.current_step` is not incremented after a replan (new step 0 of new remaining\\n  plan is the next question)\\n- Full run against S2 corpus (missing litigation register) demonstrates at least one\\n  replan cycle in the JSONL log\\n\\n**Tests:**\\n- Run `python eval/harness.py --scenario S2` — verify JSONL log contains a `\\\"replan\\\"`\\n  event\\n- Verify the final report for S2 contains a gap note about litigation, not a false\\n  clean finding\\n- Verify the loop still terminates within `MAX_ITERATIONS`\\n\\n**Risks:**\\n- Step index management during replan is easy to get wrong. Off-by-one means the agent\\n  skips the first new step or repeats the last completed step.\\n\\n**Engineering quality evidence:**\\n- JSONL trace shows the exact moment of replanning, the reason, and the new steps.\\n  A reviewer can follow the agent's decision-making without reading source code.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Milestone 3 Gate\\n\\nRun `python eval/harness.py --all`. All four scenarios must complete without crashing.\\nS1 should score above 60%. S2 and S3 should each contain at least one gap note in their\\nJSONL traces. S4 should produce a conflict note on IP-02.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Milestone 4 — Evaluation Run and Results\\n\\n**Goal:** Run the full eval harness, save results, and document what was learned.\\nThis is the 30% deliverable.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Task 4.1 — Full Evaluation Run\\n\\n**Goal:** Execute all four scenarios, save results to `results/eval_results.json`,\\nand verify the output is well-formed.\\n\\n**Files affected:**\\n- `results/eval_results.json` (create via harness)\\n\\n**Acceptance criteria:**\\n- `python eval/harness.py --all --output results/eval_results.json` completes without error\\n- JSON output contains one entry per scenario with: scenario ID, score, per-criterion\\n  verdicts, judge reasoning, and report excerpt\\n- At least one scenario has `scenario_pass: false` — confirming the harness finds real\\n  weaknesses\\n\\n**Tests:**\\n- Load `results/eval_results.json` in Python and verify structure matches expected schema\\n- Verify at least one criterion has verdict `\\\"FAIL\\\"` across the full run\\n- Verify all four scenario IDs are present\\n\\n**Risks:**\\n- OpenAI judge calls are slow (10 criteria × 4 scenarios = 40 API calls). Budget ~3-5\\n  minutes for a full eval run.\\n- Cost: 40 gpt-4o calls. At typical prompt sizes, estimate ~$0.10-0.20 total.\\n\\n**Engineering quality evidence:**\\n- Eval results reveal genuine weaknesses. An honest result table is more valuable to\\n  reviewers than a perfect score.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Task 4.2 — Eval Analysis (README Section)\\n\\n**Goal:** Write the evaluation findings section of the README. Document what the\\nresults revealed, what the agent does well, and what would be improved with more time.\\n\\n**Files affected:**\\n- `README.md` (create or extend)\\n\\n**Acceptance criteria:**\\n- Describes the eval methodology: LLM-as-judge at temperature=0, adversarial prompts,\\n  ground-truth documents given to judge\\n- References actual scores from `results/eval_results.json`\\n- Honestly names at least one criterion the agent consistently fails or partially passes\\n- Explains what the failure reveals about the agent's limitations\\n- Describes one concrete improvement that would address the failure\\n\\n**Risks:**\\n- Temptation to cherry-pick results or explain away failures. Resist this.\\n  Reviewers weight honest analysis above high scores.\\n\\n**Engineering quality evidence:**\\n- The analysis demonstrates that the eval rubric was written before the agent was built.\\n  A rubric that was written afterward would not produce honest failures.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Milestone 5 — README, Example Run, and Polish\\n\\n**Goal:** Complete all written deliverables and verify the repository can be run cold.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Task 5.1 — Example Run\\n\\n**Goal:** Execute the agent on Scenario S1 (full corpus, happy path), capture the full\\nstdout output, and save it as `examples/example_run.txt`.\\n\\n**Files affected:**\\n- `examples/example_run.txt` (create)\\n\\n**Acceptance criteria:**\\n- Output shows: plan generation, at least 3 tool calls, at least one observation per\\n  investigation category, a replan or conflict detection, and the final report\\n- Output is unedited — captured directly from stdout\\n\\n**Tests:**\\n- Read the example run and verify it is coherent and follows the logged event format\\n- Verify the final report in the example addresses the acquisition goal explicitly\\n\\n**Risks:**\\n- If the agent produces a poor output on first run, re-run with a fresh timestamp.\\n  Do not edit the output.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Task 5.2 — README\\n\\n**Goal:** Write the complete README. It is a scored artifact.\\n\\n**Files affected:**\\n- `README.md` (complete)\\n\\n**Acceptance criteria:**\\n- Sections: Overview, How to Run, How the Agent Works, Key Design Decisions,\\n  Evaluation, What I Would Do With More Time, Time Allocation\\n- \\\"How the Agent Works\\\" explains plan → act → observe → adapt in plain English,\\n  not code\\n- \\\"Key Design Decisions\\\" covers: LLM-as-judge eval, structured state vs message history,\\n  keyword search vs embeddings, why `context.py` and `tracer.py` were removed\\n- \\\"Time Allocation\\\" is honest about where time was spent and what was cut\\n- Run instructions work on a clean clone with only `pip install openai` and\\n  `OPEN_AI_KEY` set\\n\\n**Tests:**\\n- Follow the run instructions on a clean directory — verify they work without\\n  prior knowledge of the project\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Task 5.3 — Repository Hygiene\\n\\n**Goal:** Ensure the repository is clean and presentable before submission.\\n\\n**Files affected:**\\n- `.gitignore` (verify `logs/`, `results/`, `.env` are excluded)\\n- `requirements.txt` (create — `openai` only)\\n- `build_sessions/` (create directory, export Claude Code session logs)\\n\\n**Acceptance criteria:**\\n- `git status` shows no untracked secrets or credentials\\n- `requirements.txt` lists only `openai`\\n- `build_sessions/` contains raw session logs, unedited\\n- No `__pycache__`, `.env`, or log files committed\\n\\n**Risks:**\\n- `.env` containing the OpenAI key must not be committed. Verify `.gitignore` covers it\\n  before first commit.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Risk Order Rationale\\n\\nTasks are ordered so that the highest-risk items are validated earliest:\\n\\n1. **State and tools first (M1):** Pure Python, no API calls. Validates the data model\\n   and tool robustness before spending API budget.\\n2. **Plan and conclude before the full loop (M2.1 before M2.3):** Validates LLM call\\n   quality before wiring the loop. A bad plan prompt is caught early.\\n3. **Full loop before replanning (M2 before M3):** The happy path must work before\\n   testing recovery. A broken loop makes replan debugging impossible.\\n4. **Eval before README (M4 before M5):** Actual results inform what to write. Writing\\n   the README before running eval produces claims that may not match evidence.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Ten-Minute Readability Checklist\\n\\nA reviewer with no prior context should be able to understand the full system in ten\\nminutes by reading in this order:\\n\\n1. `README.md` — what it does and why (2 min)\\n2. `agent/runner.py` — the loop (2 min)\\n3. `agent/planner.py` — the LLM calls (2 min)\\n4. `agent/tools.py` — the tools (1 min)\\n5. `agent/state.py` — the data model (30 sec)\\n6. `examples/example_run.txt` — a real run (2 min)\\n\\nIf any file takes longer than its allocated time, it is too long.\\n\"},\"tool_use_id\":\"toolu_vrtx_013U2UhVBDeonvT9AA6o62V9\"}\n"

