2026-07-14 00:50:45.973 [info] From claude: 2026-07-13T22:50:45.972Z [DEBUG] Hooks: Checking first line for async: {"session_id":"[REDACTED]","transcript_path":"C:\\Users\\z00571dh\\.claude\\projects\\c--Users-z00571dh-Documents-assignment\\1259c791-eb4e-46ae-b33e-663aba03788a.jsonl","cwd":"C:\\Users\\z00571dh\\Documents\\assignment","prompt_id":"0cc1d1e5-387b-4ef2-a228-c21e99fc7fca","permission_mode":"acceptEdits","effort":{"level":"medium"},"hook_event_name":"PreToolUse","tool_name":"Write","tool_input":{"file_path":"c:\\Users\\z00571dh\\Documents\\assignment\\README.md","content":"# Legal Investigation Agent\n\nAutonomous due diligence agent for M&A legal review. Given a natural language goal and a corpus of legal documents, the agent plans an investigation, reads documents, records findings and conflicts, and produces a structured prose report.\n\n## Setup\n\n```bash\npip install openai\n```\n\nCreate a `.env` file in the project root:\n\n```\nOPENAI_KEY=sk-...\n```\n\nPython 3.10+ required (uses `match` statement and `Literal` type hints).\n\n## Running the agent\n\n```bash\npython agent/runner.py \"Can Orion Capital safely acquire Nexus Legal Technologies?\" data/documents\n```\n\nThe agent:\n1. Lists available documents\n2. Plans 5–10 investigation questions covering all five due diligence categories\n3. Loops: selects a tool, executes it, observes the result, decides to continue / replan / conclude\n4. Writes a timestamped JSONL trace to `logs/`\n5. Prints a structured prose report to stdout\n\nLog events printed to stdout: `[PLAN]`, `[TOOL]`, `[RESULT]`, `[OBSERVE]`, `[DECIDE]`, `[REPLAN]`, `[GUARD]`, `[CONCLUDE]`.\n\n## Running the evaluation harness\n\n```bash\n# Single scenario\npython eval/harness.py --scenario S1\n\n# All scenarios with JSON output\npython eval/harness.py --all --output results/eval_results.json\n```\n\nFour scenarios are defined in `eval/scenarios.py`:\n\n| ID | Name | Corpus | Min required passes |\n|----|------|--------|---------------------|\n| S1 | Full Corpus — Happy Path | All 7 documents | 5 / 5 |\n| S2 | Missing Litigation Register | 6 documents | 3 / 5 |\n| S3 | Missing IP Assignment | 6 documents | 3 / 5 |\n| S4 | IP Conflict Detection — Narrow Corpus | 2 documents | 1 / 5 |\n\nScoring uses an adversarial LLM judge (gpt-4o, temperature=0). Ten rubric criteria are defined in `eval/rubric.py`; five are required.\n\n## Architecture\n\nFour source files. No frameworks.\n\n```\nagent/state.py     — Note and InvestigationState dataclasses\nagent/tools.py     — list_files, read_file, search_in_file (pure file I/O)\nagent/planner.py   — all OpenAI calls: plan, select_tool, observe, replan, conclude\nagent/runner.py    — the agent loop (plan → loop → conclude) and dual-sink logging\n```\n\nSee `docs/architecture.md` for the full design rationale.\n\n**Loop invariants:**\n- State passed to every LLM call is an O(1) snapshot (remaining steps + notes), not accumulated message history.\n- Tool results are never accumulated — only the note extracted from them is kept.\n- The loop exits on three conditions: planner decides `conclude`, plan is exhausted, or 20-iteration guard fires.\n\n## Known limitations\n\nThe agent uses keyword search (`search_in_file`) rather than embeddings. This means a query for \"IP ownership\" will not match a document that uses \"intellectual property\" without that exact phrase. During evaluation, this caused missed matches when the agent chose a search term that did not appear verbatim in the relevant document. The fix is to add a `read_file` fallback step whenever `search_in_file` returns empty — the planner prompt instructs this, but the LLM does not always follow it reliably.\n\nA secondary weakness is that `conclude` is called once at the end from `state.notes` only. If the planner failed to record a conflict as a `conflict`-kind note (recording it as a `finding` instead), the summariser has no signal that a cross-document tension exists. This was observed in early testing with the Imperial licence / IP assignment conflict (IP-02): the agent found both documents but did not always classify the note as `conflict`. Addressed in the `observe` prompt with explicit instructions, but the LLM remains non-deterministic on this classification.\n"},"tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01FPeGYXzDQNQqzn1JFTL3mm"}

2026-07-14 00:50:45.973 [info] From claude: 2026-07-13T22:50:45.972Z [DEBUG] Hooks: Parsed initial response: {"session_id":"[REDACTED]","transcript_path":"C:\\Users\\z00571dh\\.claude\\projects\\c--Users-z00571dh-Documents-assignment\\1259c791-eb4e-46ae-b33e-663aba03788a.jsonl","cwd":"C:\\Users\\z00571dh\\Documents\\assignment","prompt_id":"0cc1d1e5-387b-4ef2-a228-c21e99fc7fca","permission_mode":"acceptEdits","effort":{"level":"medium"},"hook_event_name":"PreToolUse","tool_name":"Write","tool_input":{"file_path":"c:\\Users\\z00571dh\\Documents\\assignment\\README.md","content":"# Legal Investigation Agent\n\nAutonomous due diligence agent for M&A legal review. Given a natural language goal and a corpus of legal documents, the agent plans an investigation, reads documents, records findings and conflicts, and produces a structured prose report.\n\n## Setup\n\n```bash\npip install openai\n```\n\nCreate a `.env` file in the project root:\n\n```\nOPENAI_KEY=sk-...\n```\n\nPython 3.10+ required (uses `match` statement and `Literal` type hints).\n\n## Running the agent\n\n```bash\npython agent/runner.py \"Can Orion Capital safely acquire Nexus Legal Technologies?\" data/documents\n```\n\nThe agent:\n1. Lists available documents\n2. Plans 5–10 investigation questions covering all five due diligence categories\n3. Loops: selects a tool, executes it, observes the result, decides to continue / replan / conclude\n4. Writes a timestamped JSONL trace to `logs/`\n5. Prints a structured prose report to stdout\n\nLog events printed to stdout: `[PLAN]`, `[TOOL]`, `[RESULT]`, `[OBSERVE]`, `[DECIDE]`, `[REPLAN]`, `[GUARD]`, `[CONCLUDE]`.\n\n## Running the evaluation harness\n\n```bash\n# Single scenario\npython eval/harness.py --scenario S1\n\n# All scenarios with JSON output\npython eval/harness.py --all --output results/eval_results.json\n```\n\nFour scenarios are defined in `eval/scenarios.py`:\n\n| ID | Name | Corpus | Min required passes |\n|----|------|--------|---------------------|\n| S1 | Full Corpus — Happy Path | All 7 documents | 5 / 5 |\n| S2 | Missing Litigation Register | 6 documents | 3 / 5 |\n| S3 | Missing IP Assignment | 6 documents | 3 / 5 |\n| S4 | IP Conflict Detection — Narrow Corpus | 2 documents | 1 / 5 |\n\nScoring uses an adversarial LLM judge (gpt-4o, temperature=0). Ten rubric criteria are defined in `eval/rubric.py`; five are required.\n\n## Architecture\n\nFour source files. No frameworks.\n\n```\nagent/state.py     — Note and InvestigationState dataclasses\nagent/tools.py     — list_files, read_file, search_in_file (pure file I/O)\nagent/planner.py   — all OpenAI calls: plan, select_tool, observe, replan, conclude\nagent/runner.py    — the agent loop (plan → loop → conclude) and dual-sink logging\n```\n\nSee `docs/architecture.md` for the full design rationale.\n\n**Loop invariants:**\n- State passed to every LLM call is an O(1) snapshot (remaining steps + notes), not accumulated message history.\n- Tool results are never accumulated — only the note extracted from them is kept.\n- The loop exits on three conditions: planner decides `conclude`, plan is exhausted, or 20-iteration guard fires.\n\n## Known limitations\n\nThe agent uses keyword search (`search_in_file`) rather than embeddings. This means a query for \"IP ownership\" will not match a document that uses \"intellectual property\" without that exact phrase. During evaluation, this caused missed matches when the agent chose a search term that did not appear verbatim in the relevant document. The fix is to add a `read_file` fallback step whenever `search_in_file` returns empty — the planner prompt instructs this, but the LLM does not always follow it reliably.\n\nA secondary weakness is that `conclude` is called once at the end from `state.notes` only. If the planner failed to record a conflict as a `conflict`-kind note (recording it as a `finding` instead), the summariser has no signal that a cross-document tension exists. This was observed in early testing with the Imperial licence / IP assignment conflict (IP-02): the agent found both documents but did not always classify the note as `conflict`. Addressed in the `observe` prompt with explicit instructions, but the LLM remains non-deterministic on this classification.\n"},"tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01FPeGYXzDQNQqzn1JFTL3mm"}
